1171–1205","1197–Male":"1197–Deceased","1198–Male":"1198–Deceased","1148–1208":"1148–1208","1148–1210":"1148–1210","1205":"1205","1148":"1148","1169":"1169","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","1198":"1198","1197":"1197","1174":"1174","about 1198":"about 1198","1171":"1171","1208":"1208","about 1197":"about 1197","Wolston, Warwickshire, England":"Wolston, Warwickshire, England","Chetwode, Buckinghamshire, England":"Chetwode, Buckinghamshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Strange","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Wiltshire and Gloucestershire): nickname for a newcomer to a district, from Middle English <i>strange</i> ‘foreign’ (Old French <i>estrange</i>, Latin <i>extraneus</i>, from <i>extra</i> ‘outside’).","Irish (Antrim): this name is also common in Ireland, where, in addition to its English etymology, it may represent an Anglicized form of any of several Irish names containing the element <i>gall</i> ‘stranger’, e.g.   Doyle  ,   Gallagher  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Stranger","meanings":["English: nickname for a newcomer to an area, from Middle English <i>stra(u)nger(e)</i> ‘stranger, foreigner’ (Old French <i>estrangier</i>). Compare   Strange  ."]},{"name":"Doyle","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Sean, Kieran, Seamus, Aileen, Dermot, Liam, Niall, Brennan, Brigid, Conal, Conan, Donal.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Dubhghaill</b> ‘descendant of <i>Dubhghall</i>’, a personal name composed of the elements <i>dubh</i> ‘black’ + <i>gall</i> ‘stranger’. This was used as a byname for Scandinavians, in particular to distinguish the darker-haired Danes from fair-haired Norwegians. Compare   McDougall  ,   McDowell  ."]},{"name":"Lestrange","meanings":["Irish and English: variant of   Strange   1 with fused Old French definite article <i>le</i>.","Irish: in Ireland, adopted for <b>Mac Conchoigchríche</b> ‘son of <i>Cúchoigcriche</i>’, a personal name meaning ‘hound of the borderland’. <i>Lestrange</i> was adopted for <b>Mac Conchoigchríche</b> probably due to the presence of a prominent family of Lestrange, of similar meaning, who settled in the counties of Westmeath and Offaly in the 16th century."]}]},{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Sybil","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."],"variants":[{"name":"Sybilla","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Sibilla","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Sybille","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Sybil</b> ."]},{"name":"Sibella","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Sybil Strange de Fredville was born in 1174, in Wolston, Warwickshire, England, her father, Roger De Fredville, was 27 and her mother, Annabel Strange, was 26. She married Robert De Chetwode in 1197, in Wolston, Warwickshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died in 1200, in Chetwode, Buckinghamshire, England, at the age of 26."},"et":{"1174–1200":"1174–1200","1171–1205":"1171–1205","1197–Male":"1197–Surnud","1198–Male":"1198–Surnud","1148–1208":"1148–1208","1148–1210":"1148–1210","1205":"1205","1148":"1148","1169":"1169","1200":"1200","1210":"1210","1198":"1198","1197":"1197","1174":"1174","about 1198":"umbes 1198","117